{
  "texts": [
    "By clustering pages generated from similar templates and distilling the language model's decisions into reusable extraction rules, we achieve web-scale processing efficiency while preserving the quality of the core extraction pipeline.",
    "① PRE-PROCESSING Raw HTMLTransformations:• Remove non-content tags• Simplify attributes • Block-level chunking • Partial truncation Mapping HTML Original structure Key Design: Dual representation ensures compact model input while preserving faithful reconstruction capability Simplified HTML Compact input for model <html> <Block 1>XXX</Block 1> <Block 2>XXX</Block 2> <Block 3>XXX</Block 3> </html> MinerU-HTML-Classifier 0.6B Decoder-only LM Sequential Classification Constrained Decoding Structured JSON Response{ \"block1\": \"other\", \"block2\": \"main\", \"block3\": \"other\", } ③ POST-PROCESSING ② CLASSIFICATION Structured JSON ResponseMain/other JSON Operations:• Project labels to Mapping HTML blocks • Prune blocks labeled as \"other\"• Assemble valid DOM subtree Main-HTML• Clean main-content only • Sub DOM-tree of raw HTML We first describe the single-document extraction framework (2.1.1), then present the scaling strategy (2.1.2).",
    "Core Extraction PipelineMinerU-HTML transforms raw HTML documents into clean Main-HTML through a three-stage pipeline, as illustrated in Figure 1.",
    "The architecture is designed to address two key challenges: (1) reducing the computational burden of processing lengthy HTML markup, and (2) ensuring that the extracted content remains faithful to the original document without hallucination.The pipeline operates as follows.",
    "In the pre-processing stage, the input HTML is partitioned into semantic blocks, generating two synchronized representations: Simplified HTML, which strips away rendering-oriented markup to create compact input for the language model, and Mapping HTML, which preserves the original block structure to enable faithful reconstruction."
  ]
}